= Background and Related Work <sec-background-related-work>
In this section, we will review the background and related work in the areas of Linux kernel development, Rust-based kernels, ABI compatibility, fuzzing and testing techniques and also the application of large language models in the software testing field. 

== Linux kernel and Rust-based kernels
Linux kernel is developed based on Unix-like kernel and it is written mostly in C. The key design of the Linux kernel is monolithic kernel@love2010linux, which means that all core os services runs in a single kernel address space and interact via direct function calls. In this design, there will be no IPC, no message passing, no internal context switches and so on. IPC and context switch in microkernel design will cost microseconds level latency, but in monolithic kernel design, the latency of the function calls can be reduced to nanoseconds level. In this case, linux kernel can provide better performance than the microkernel design and this design helps the Linux kernel easy to integrate with new hardware and software. However, the monolithic kernel design also has some drawbacks. because all components share the kernel space, a bug in one component can potentially crash the entire system. Due to the complex interactions between different components, it can be difficult to isolate and debug issues. The c programming language itself is a powerful but unsafe programming language because of its lack of memory safety features. This increases the risk of security vulnerabilities and system crashes@Reshetova2018. Rust, a modern systems programming language, has been gaining popularity in recent years due to its memeory safety, concurrency safety and high performance without relying on a garbage collector@bugden2022rustprogramminglanguagesafety. It achieves this through a strong static type system and its ownership and borrowing model. Rust can prevent common memory bugs at compile time including buffer overflows, use-after-free and so on. It eliminates a large class of vulnerabilities common in C/C++@kan2020executableoperationalsemanticsrust. Because of these advantages, there has been growing interest in using Rust for kernel development. The Linux kernel community has started to accept Rust code and there are already some Rust-based kernel like Asterinas@aster, rCore@rcore and Kerla@kerla. However, despite these benefits, an important open question remains: whether Rust-based kernels behave consistently with the Linux kernel at the Application Binary Interface (ABI) level. Such consistency is essential for ensuring compatibility and correctness across different kernel implementations.
== ABI Compatibility
ABI (Application Binary Interface) defines the low-level interface between an application and the operating system including system call conventions, data types and observable behaviors such as return values, side effects and error codes. ABI compatibility means that a program compiled staticly for a given ABI can run correctly on another kernel implementing the same ABI without modification. Also, they are expected to produce consistent observable behaviors like the same return values or the same return error codes when executing the same system calls with the same arguments@binarylevel. In the context of kernel development, many applications and kernel modules are built on top of the Linux kernel ABI. Many programs rely on specific behaviors of the Linux kernel, some of the programs may even rely on specific return values or error codes. Many library developers use `switch` or other control flow statements to handle different return values and error codes. That is to say, even if the Rust-based kernels can successfully execute the same system calls, they may still produce different return values or error codes which may result in unexpected behaviors of the applications if they do not ensure ABI Compatibility with the Linux kernel. In this case, researchers find it crucial to evaluate the ABI Compatibility of Rust-based kernels with the Linux kernel. However, evaluating ABI Compatibility is a non-trivial task. Many kernels which claims that they are Linux-compatible seldom give a detailed analysis of their ABI compatibility with the Linux kernel. A static analysis tool called System Call Matching Language(SCML) is proposed to analyze the syscall interface of a kernel and compare it with the Linux kernel. However, it only focuses on the flags and bits that implemented in the kernel and it does not evaluate the return values, error codes and side effects of the system calls. To the best of our knowledge, there is no existing framework or benchmark that can systematically evaluate the ABI Compatibility of Rust-based kernels with the Linux kernel. 
== Fuzzing and Testing Techniques
Fuzzing is a widely used technique for finding bugs and vulnerabilities in software. It involves generating random or semi-random inputs and feed them to a specific target program to trigger unexpected behaviors or crashes@fuzzing_challenges. These kinds of programs are called fuzz drivers or fuzz targets. Fuzz drivers can be generated manually or automatically. They ensures a sequence of API calls with specific arguments to trigger specific code paths in the target program. Because developing fuzz drivers manually can be time-consuming, there are many existing researches on automatic fuzz driver generation@promptfuzz@PromeFuzz. Other researches focus on the input generating process and they use machine learning techniques to generate more effective inputs@fuzzing_input. However, most of the existing fuzzing techniques are designed for testing user-space applications and they are not directly applicable to kernel testing. Kernel fuzzing is more challenge than user-space fuzzing because of the complexity of the kernel and the difficulty of reproducing bugs. There are some existing kernel fuzzing tools like Syzkaller@syzkaller,Trinity@jones2010trinity and so on. However, these tools are designed mainly for finding bugs and vulnerabilities in the Linux kernel and it may take great effort to transpart them to do kernel fuzzing on other kernels. Also, fuzzing techniques are not designed for evaluating ABI Compatibility because they do not focus on the return values, error codes and side effects of the system calls. They find bugs by triggering crashes or hangs, but they do not evaluate the correctness of the behaviors of the system calls. 

Except fuzzing, there are also some other testing techniques for kernel testing like unit testing, integration testing and so on. Unit testing is a software testing technique that focuses on testing individual units or components of a software system in isolation. It can help to find bugs that will not cause crashes but can cause unexpected behaviors@unit_test. Integration testing is a software testing technique that focuses on testing the interactions between different components of a software system. It can help to find bugs that arise from the interactions between different components@integration_testing. However, these testing techniques are not designed for evaluating ABI Compatibility because they do not focus on the return values, error codes and side effects of the system calls. They are designed for testing the functionality of the software rather than evaluating the compatibility of the software with other implementations. Differential testing is a software testing technique that focuses on testing the same program in different environments or with different implementations. This can help us to find incompatibility issues between different kernels because if two kernels claim that they pursue the same ABI, they are expected to produce the same return values, error codes and side effects when executing the same system calls with the same arguments. Through this kind of testing, we can find the incompatibility issues between the Rust-based kernels and the Linux kernel. However, there is no existing framework or benchmark that can systematically evaluate the ABI Compatibility of Rust-based kernels with the Linux kernel through differential testing.
== Large Language Models in Software Testing
LLM(Large Language Models) is a type of machine learning model that is train on a large corpus of dataset based on the transformer architecture@LLM_tansformer. A well-known example of LLM is GPT developed by OpenAI@radford2018improving. The core idea of LLM is to learn the statistical patterns and relationships in the training data and use the knowledge to generate new date or make predictions based on the given sequence of previous tokens. LLM has been applied in various fields including natural language processing, computer vision and so on. Compared to the traditional machine learning models, one of the great advantages of LLM is that LLM has a context-awared ability which means that LLM can understand the context of the input in nature language and generate more relevant and coherent output. This is extremely outstanding in code generation tasks. LLM can generate code snippets that strictly follow the instructions and requirements given in the prompt, while other machine learning models may not be able to generate code that is syntactically correct or semantically meaningful when following the prompts@LLM_code_generation. 

In the software testing field, LLM has two main ways to be applied: static and dynamic. In static applications, researchers can directly feed the source code of the target program to the LLM and ask it to analyze the code to see whether there are any potential bugs or vulnerabilities in the code@nie2025vulnllmrspecializedreasoningllm. This kind of application is called static code analysis. It is quite convenient because it does not require the target program to be executed and it can analyze the code in a more comprehensive way. However, this kind of method suffer heavily in false negative because the LLM may not be able to understand the code completely if the code is too complex or the code comes from a domain taht the LLM is not familiar with. Another way to apply LLM in software testing is dynamic application which means that we can use LLM to generate tests cases for the target program and then execute the test cases to see whether there are any bugs or vulnerabilities in the target program. This kind of application is called dynamic test case generation. It some specific area, it performs better than the static code analysis bacause it can generate test cases that can trigger specific code paths in the target program and it can also evaluate the behaviors of the target program when executing the test cases, while static analysis suffer from complex code and perform badly. However, dynamic test case generation also has some drawbacks. It may require a lot of compuational resources to generate the test cases. Also, the tests cases can sometimes be too strict or too simple. But when it comes to evaluating ABI Compatibility, dynamic test case generation is a more powerful method because we need to see the detailed output of different kernels. Therefore, leveraging LLMs to automatically generate dynamic test cases presents a promising approach to systematically evaluate and uncover ABI inconsistencies between Rust-based kernels and the Linux kernel.